<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
<title>@HI{{no}}</title>
<link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="japanese.css"/>
<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
</head>

@GRMIDX{{index="@HI{{no}}" grammar="@HI{{no}}"}}

<body>

<h1>@HI{{no}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N1{{}}@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} @N2{{}}
<li> @Splain{{}}@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} ...
<li> @S{{}}@HI{{@EM{{no}}}}.
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="modifier">@HI{{@EM{{no}}}}</a> can be used between two nouns to indicate possession.
If the context is understood, the second noun can be omitted.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{koreha@FG{{@KJ{{tall^tree}}:tagaki}}san@EM{{no}}@KJ{{umbrella}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This is Takagi's umbrella.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be used between two nouns to indicate position or location.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{desk}}@EM{{no}}@KJ{{above}}}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      on the desk
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be used between two nouns to indicate that the first noun modifies the 
second in terms of kind or category.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field^before^life}}ha@KJ{{england^word}}@EM{{no}}@KJ{{before^life}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yamada is a teacher of English.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="apposition">@HI{{@EM{{no}}}}</a> can be used between two nouns to indicate that the two nouns are in apposition.
This shows that the two nouns are identical.
The first noun shows an attribute about the second noun and so gives more information about it.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kochiraga@FG{{@KJ{{assistant^mountain}}:sayama}}san'noo@KJ{{elder*sister}}sann@EM{{no}}@FG{{@KJ{{thousand^incense^child}}:chikako}}sandesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This is Chikako, Sayama's elder sister.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be used in place of @HI{{ga}} to mark the subject in a
<a href="grammar-relative-clause.html">relative clause</a>.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{koreha@KJ{{slope^book}}sann@EM{{no}}@KJ{{sketch}}ita@KJ{{oil^picture}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      This is the oil painting that Sakamoto painted.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="indefinite">@HI{{@EM{{no}}}}</a> can be used following an adjective or a relative clause
to form an indefinite pronoun.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha@KJ{{large}}ki@EM{{no}}wo@KJ{{buy}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I bought a large one.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be to <a href="grammar-no-nominaliser.html">nominalise</a> verbs and adjectives.
In this use it is a simple nominaliser corresponding to "~ing" or "what".

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he^woman}}ga@KJ{{longing}}shii@EM{{no}}ha,@KJ{{new}}shii@KT{{piano}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      What she wants is a new piano.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be to <a href="grammar-no-nominaliser.html">nominalise</a> verbs of perception.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{woman}}no@KJ{{person}}ga@KJ{{song}}tteiru@EM{{no}}ga@KJ{{hear}}koemasune.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      You can hear a woman singing can't you?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="ending">@HI{{@EM{{no}}}}</a> can be used as a sentence ending particle as a 
question marker in colloquial sentences.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{meeting^company}},@KJ{{book^hit}}niyameru@EM{{no}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      You're really quitting the company?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be used as a sentence ending particle to soften a sentence. This is usually used by women.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}},@KJ{{come^month}}@KT{{furansu}}ni@KJ{{detain^study}}suru@EM{{no}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Next month I'm going to France to study.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{no}}}} can be used as a sentence ending particle to indicate a mild command.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{Sonnnakotoiwanai@EM{{no}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Don't say things like that.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@N1{{}}@HI{{no}}@N2{{}} can mean:
<ul>
<li> @N2{{}} belongs to a group identified by @N1{{}} (e.g "Mr. Miller is an IMC employee.")
<li> @N2{{}} is of a type described by @N1{{}} (e.g. "This is a book about computers.")
<li> @N2{{}} is made in the country or by the company described by @N1{{}}
</ul>
</p>
